{"source_key":"sha256-0c6145c72f7c68906237355bfab38a2e","record_index":221,"record_hash":"sha256:1e20adcdebf86fa2deba93030686dfd67363df734773b056eeb40d4568798552","timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:09:04.543Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Lane 2 Recommendation**\\n\\nBuild **Agent Trail generation as a separate worker/service**. Keep Forge as the Next.js UI/API facade.\\n\\nPutting the generator inside Forge is only sane if Forge is deployed as a long-lived container with a persistent volume. If Forge is on Vercel-style serverless, it is the wrong runtime.\\n\\n**Why Vercel/Next routes are a bad fit**\\n\\nAgent Trail needs:\\n\\n- a real local Git repo/cache\\n- writable persistent storage for `.git/git-meta.sqlite`\\n- `git` or equivalent Git plumbing\\n- native Rust/NAPI loading or a Rust binary\\n- job locking, retries, cleanup, and probably queue semantics\\n\\nVercel Functions do not match that well:\\n\\n- Node Functions have **read-only filesystem plus `/tmp` scratch only, up to 500 MB**: [Vercel runtimes](https://vercel.com/docs/functions/runtimes)\\n- Functions scale to zero and are request-invocation based: [Vercel Functions lifecycle](https://vercel.com/docs/functions)\\n- Max duration is bounded, currently 300s Hobby and 800s Pro/Enterprise with Fluid Compute: [Vercel limits](https://vercel.com/docs/functions/limitations)\\n- `waitUntil` is still bound by the function timeout: [Vercel KB](https://examples.vercel.[REDACTED:entropy])\\n- Native addons are possible in Node generally, and Node-API is ABI-stable: [Node-API docs](https://nodejs.org/api/n-api.html), but Next may need `serverExternalPackages`: [Next docs](https://nextjs.[REDACTED:entropy])\\n- Vercel build image has `git`, but that is build-time docs, not a durable runtime contract for a Git cache daemon: [Vercel build image](https://vercel.com/docs/builds/build-image)\\n\\n**Better hosting shape**\\n\\nUse a container/VM worker with a persistent volume:\\n\\n| Platform | Fit | Notes |\\n|---|---:|---|\\n| Fly.io | Good | Volumes are persistent regular directories; root FS is ephemeral. [Docs](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/) |\\n| Render | Good | Paid services/workers can attach persistent disks; default FS is ephemeral. [Docs](https://render.com/docs/disks) |\\n| Railway | Good | Volumes mount read/write into a service; supports Docker/Nixpacks and apt packages. [Docs](https://docs.railway.com/develop/volumes) |\\n| Vercel Sandbox | Interesting, not default | Has Git, writable FS, sudo, command execution, snapshots, but normal SDK docs still frame FS as ephemeral; persistence is beta. [Docs](https://vercel.com/docs/vercel-sandbox/reference/readme), [beta persistence](https://vercel.[REDACTED:entropy]) |\\n\\n**Pierre/code.storage angle**\\n\\nPierre can help as a remote mirror/cache, not as the local filesystem. Code Storage supports public GitHub sync and generic HTTPS Git sync:\\n\\n- [Public GitHub Sync](https://code.[REDACTED:entropy])\\n- [Generic HTTPS Git Sync](https://code.storage/changelog/generic-https-git-sync)\\n- [GitHub Sync guide](https://code.storage/docs/guides/github-sync)\\n\\nBut current `git-meta-lib`/`but-agentlog` wants repo-path semantics. So even with Pierre, the generator still needs a local scratch/cache repo unless GitButler APIs are changed to read GitMeta directly from a remote object API.\\n\\n**Call**\\n\\nDo this split:\\n\\n- **Forge repo:** URL replacement, public route, JSON contract, UI, status polling.\\n- **Generator service repo:** clone/fetch/cache repos, materialize GitMeta, run `but-agentlog`, store projected result.\\n- **GitButler repo:** expose the clean `but-agentlog` projection API.\\n\\nIf the generator is separate, I’d lean toward a small **Rust HTTP worker** instead of Node+NAPI. NAPI is cleaner only if the Rust has to run inside Forge’s Node process. Separate service means we can skip that bridge entirely.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:09:04.543Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}